node.text:
“Perhaps most indelibly, Fanone offered his take on the rioters who’d heeded his pleas for mercy. “A lot of people have asked me my thoughts on the individuals in the crowd that helped me,” he drawled. “I think the conclusion I’ve come to is, like, thank you”—here he paused and squinted—“but f-ck you for being there.”

I posted the accompanying article from @time magazine, which is absolutely worth the read, on my Twitter @AGirlHasNoPres and in my stories.

node.text:
This guy is wonderful and it makes me sick to my stomach when he talks about the things that he saw that day. The worst possible people stormed the Capitol on January 6th. Privileged, entitled, and presumptuous that they were just going to walk in and no one would try to stop them.

Turns out every officer there wasn’t the kind of officer that would remove  barricades for them and unlock doors. They were enough of those, but I’m thankful this guy wasn’t one of them. But it sure sounds like they put them through hell.

node.text:
I haven’t seen this on the news at all. Why are we not seeing stories like this? It’s absolutely awful and the world to know what’s going on. We don’t care when black and brown people die, no matter what the cause.

“Thirteen badly decomposed corpses were recovered from the boat at first. Then, after the water was drained from the bottom, officers found another body and some skeletal remains.
There were no lifejackets, no trace of food, and evidence that only a scant amount of fuel had been brought to run a 40hp outboard engine that was far too small to properly power the 42ft-long boat, which was registered in Mauritania. Police found 1,000 Swiss francs, €50 and a number of mobile phones. Those that weren’t irretrievably corroded were traced to Mauritania and Mali.
Even before postmortem examinations determined that 13 of the 15 bodies were those of African men, Nurse and his colleagues had begun to suspect that those aboard had not been trying to reach the Caribbean. “We know that people from other African countries stop in Mauritania to get a boat with the hope of getting to Europe,” he said. But those aboard the boat registered as AG231 – 15 people who died of hunger, thirst and exposure – appear to have overshot the continent by almost the entire width of the north Atlantic.
Six weeks later, Nurse got a phone call from Deputy Commissioner Rodney Adams of the Turks and Caicos police. A boat carrying 15 bodies had been discovered drifting in the waters off Grand Turk.” 
I posted the link on my Twitter @AGirlHasNoPres More @guardian

“Piercey reiterated her concerns Friday during a news conference with Education Commissioner Penny Schwinn. 

Crowded pediatric hospitals are the result of a spike of respiratory syncytial virus, or RSV, followed by the sudden resurgence of the coronavirus, which is now spreading faster among children.
